£30,000 for texting bollards A £30,000 grant has been awarded to a bizarre new art project which enables people living in Bristol to text their bollards and lamp posts. The art project Hello Lamp Post is costing £30,000 By Daisy Bowie-Sell
3:52PM GMT 23 Jan 2013
Follow Comments
Hello Lamp Post! is the name of a bizarre £30,000 project which allows Bristol residents to text bollards, lamp posts, benches, post boxes and more. In an attempt to harness the technology behind the 'smart cities', London-based design studio PAN will set up Hello Lamp Post! in Bristol this summer. The idea is purportedly to "communicate through lamp posts, bus stops and other street furniture". The project takes advantage of technology generally used by councils for practical reasons – to highlight when a light bulb might need to be changed, for example – and uses it for playful communication. Each post box, bollard, bench and storm drain in the city has a unique code. People will be invited to write a text to a special phone number saying "Hello + the name of the object and its code". The object will then immediately text you back a question. The project was picked from a group of 93 applications for the £30,000 Playable City Award. Musician Imogen Heap was on the judging panel, which picked PAN for its "approach to public spaces, which uses inanimate objects to trigger playful interactions". Related Articles
We shouldn't sell public art - even to raise funds
