23 Jan 2013
Heap said: "I love this for its whispers on the street, guardians in dark corners, humanising our cities' appendages whose eyes and ears now have a voice. Vessels for an ever evolving conversation, connecting us together. They were there all along!" Judge Tom Uglow of Google said: "Hello Lamp Post! stood out with a potential for both art and play using existing urban furniture. It filled me with childish delight." Combining art and technology, the idea behind the commission is to to find art which utilises creative technology to 'explore the theme of the playable city. The project will begin in July this year. The award is supported by a number of organisations including Aardman, Toshiba, Univeristy of Bristol and Bristol City Council. Read more and follow the project as it develops at watershed.co.uk/playablecity
