News in brief
12:00AM BST 25 Sep 2000
THE head teacher cleared on appeal of slapping an unruly 10-year-old is expected to be interviewed by police about new allegations of mistreatment as the school faces fresh turmoil. Graham Powell, chairman of the governors and a campaigner to have Marjorie Evans, the suspended head re-instated, could be ousted by his deputy at a meeting on Thursday.
It was unclear whether the move reflected diminishing support for Mrs Evans or opposition to Mr Powell who has been vociferous in his backing of the head teacher. Yesterday, Mr Powell said he wanted to remain as chairman and re-iterated his claim that there was a "witch-hunt" by staff members and parents against Mrs Evans.
Ian Williams, solicitor for Mrs Williams, said the new allegations included shouting at noisy children in an inappropriate tone of voice.
Pilot and wife escape crash
THE pilot of a helicopter and his wife crawled from its wreckage with cuts and bruises after it plunged to the ground. Edward Meredith encountered bad weather above the 1,000 acre New Zealand Farm at Chute, Wiltshire, after taking off in good conditions from Thruxton airfield, five miles away in Hampshire. The couple were returning home to Gloucestershire from a party.
Baby hurt in explosion
A FOUR-MONTH-OLD boy was badly hurt in an explosion at a house in Fareham, Hampshire, when the owner lit a solid fuel fire fitted with a back boiler. Andrew Metcalfe escaped with minor injuries and shock, but his son Robin suffered burns to his face, airway and torso. He was seriously ill in hospital last night.
